ol.li:
Create the diskquota database. The diskquota module
          uses this database to store the list of databases where the module is enabled.
          $ createdb diskquota;

section.codeblock:
SELECT diskquota.pause();
-- perform table operations where you do not care to be notified
-- when a disk quota exceeded
SELECT diskquota.resume();

ul.li:
To avoid the chance of deadlock, you must first pause the
          diskquota extension before you drop the extension in any database:
          SELECT diskquota.pause();
DROP EXTENSION diskquota;

ol.li:
Update the diskquota extension in every database in which you
          registered the module:
          $ psql -d testdb -c "ALTER EXTENSION diskquota UPDATE TO '2.0'";

Run the following commands to create a table in the s1 schema and insert a
          small amount of data into it. The schema has no data yet, so it is not on the denylist.
          SET search_path TO s1;
CREATE TABLE a(i int);
INSERT INTO a SELECT generate_series(1,100);

Remove the quota from the s1 schema by setting it to
            -1 and again inserts a small amount of data. A 5-second sleep before
          the INSERT command ensures that the diskquota table size
          data is updated before the command is
          run.SELECT diskquota.set_schema_quota('s1', '-1');
-- Wait for 5 seconds to ensure that the denylist is updated
SELECT pg_sleep(5);
INSERT INTO a SELECT generate_series(1,100);

Set a disk quota of 1 MB for the tablespace named
         tbsp1 and the schema named s1:
         SELECT diskquota.set_schema_tablespace_quota('s1', 'tbsp1', '1MB');

Create a new table named b and insert some data:
          CREATE TABLE b(i int);
INSERT INTO b SELECT generate_series(1,100);
